STEP 15: Big O Notation — Time & Space Complexity                       [BOTH]
------------------------------------------------------------------------
  LEARN:
    WHY IT MATTERS:
      A program that works on 10 elements might time-out on 10 million.
      Big O tells you HOW your code scales with input size N.

    COMMON COMPLEXITIES (best to worst):
      O(1)        — Constant      — array access, hash map lookup
      O(log N)    — Logarithmic   — binary search, balanced BST
      O(N)        — Linear        — single loop, linear search
      O(N log N)  — Linearithmic  — merge sort, heap sort, good sorting
      O(N^2)      — Quadratic     — nested loops, bubble sort
      O(N^3)      — Cubic         — triple nested loops, naive matrix mult
      O(2^N)      — Exponential   — brute force subsets, naive recursion
      O(N!)       — Factorial     — permutation generation

    RULES:
      - Drop constants: O(2N) = O(N)
      - Drop lower terms: O(N^2 + N) = O(N^2)
      - Consider WORST CASE unless stated otherwise
      - Nested loops multiply: O(N) inside O(N) = O(N^2)
      - Sequential loops add: O(N) + O(M) = O(N+M)

    SPACE COMPLEXITY:
      - Extra memory your algorithm uses (not counting input)
      - Recursion uses O(depth) stack space
      - Creating extra array of size N = O(N) space

    BEST, AVERAGE, WORST CASE:
      Quick sort: best O(N log N), worst O(N^2) if bad pivot

    AMORTIZED ANALYSIS:
      Dynamic array push_back: usually O(1), occasionally O(N) to resize.
      Amortized = average over many operations = O(1).

