STEP 18: Polymorphism & Abstraction                                      [C++]
------------------------------------------------------------------------
  LEARN:
    COMPILE-TIME (Static) POLYMORPHISM:
      Function overloading — same name, different params
      Operator overloading — redefine operators for your class

    RUNTIME (Dynamic) POLYMORPHISM:
      Virtual functions + Base class pointer

      class Shape {
      public:
        virtual double area() = 0;  // pure virtual — makes class abstract
      };
      class Circle : public Shape {
        double area() override { return 3.14 * r * r; }
      };

      Shape* s = new Circle(5);
      s->area();  // calls Circle's area(), NOT Shape's

    VIRTUAL FUNCTION TABLE (vtable):
      Compiler creates a table of function pointers for virtual functions.
      Slight runtime overhead but enables polymorphism.

    ABSTRACT CLASS:
      Has at least one pure virtual function.
      Cannot be instantiated directly.
      Acts as interface/contract.

    VIRTUAL DESTRUCTOR:
      Always make destructor virtual in base class when using polymorphism.
      Ensures derived destructor is called properly.

    OPERATOR OVERLOADING:
      Vector operator+(const Vector& v) { ... }
      ostream& operator<<(ostream& os, const MyClass& obj) { ... }

