STEP 57: Number Theory for Competitive Programming                       [DSA]
------------------------------------------------------------------------
  LEARN:
    PRIME NUMBERS:
      Check primality: O(sqrt(N)).
      Sieve of Eratosthenes: find all primes up to N in O(N log log N).
      Segmented sieve: for primes in range [L, R].

    GCD & LCM:
      Euclidean algorithm: gcd(a, b) = gcd(b, a%b), base: gcd(a, 0) = a. O(log N).
      lcm(a, b) = (a/gcd(a,b)) * b  — divide first to prevent overflow.
      Extended Euclidean: find x, y such that ax + by = gcd(a, b).

    MODULAR ARITHMETIC:
      (a + b) % m = ((a % m) + (b % m)) % m
      (a * b) % m = ((a % m) * (b % m)) % m
      (a - b) % m = ((a % m) - (b % m) + m) % m  — add m to handle negative
      Modular inverse: a^(-1) mod m = a^(m-2) mod m  (Fermat's, when m is prime).

    FAST EXPONENTIATION:
      x^n in O(log n) using binary exponentiation.
      ll power(ll base, ll exp, ll mod) {
        ll result = 1;
        while (exp > 0) {
          if (exp & 1) result = result * base % mod;
          base = base * base % mod;
          exp >>= 1;
        }
        return result;
      }

    EULER'S TOTIENT:
      phi(n) = count of numbers in [1, n] coprime to n.
      phi(p) = p-1 for prime p.
      phi(p^k) = p^(k-1) * (p-1).
      Multiplicative: phi(mn) = phi(m)*phi(n) if gcd(m,n)=1.

    CHINESE REMAINDER THEOREM:
      System of congruences x ≡ a1 (mod m1), x ≡ a2 (mod m2), ...
      Unique solution when moduli are pairwise coprime.

    MATRIX EXPONENTIATION:
      Compute M^n in O(K^3 log n) where K = matrix size.
      Used to speed up linear recurrences: Fibonacci in O(log n).

